    dissectionAndExperiment: [
        "Dissect the coral bleaching mechanism step by step: (1) identify the normal zooxanthellae function (photosynthate supply, source of up to 90% of coral energy); (2) identify the initial insult (sea temperature rise of 1–2°C above seasonal maximum); (3) trace the cellular cascade — photosystem II dysfunction → electron transport uncoupled → reactive oxygen species generated → ROS damages both zooxanthellae and host cells → coral expels Symbiodinium; (4) identify what bleaching looks like (white calcium carbonate skeleton visible); (5) state the time threshold (4–8 weeks without zooxanthellae → coral starvation and death). For each step, write the biological term and a plain-language sentence.",
        "Dissect the diatom frustule biology: (1) identify the two valves (epitheca = larger; hypotheca = smaller) and how they interlock; (2) trace what happens at binary fission — each daughter retains one valve, synthesises one new smaller valve inside it; (3) calculate: if generation 0 cell has diameter 80 μm and each generation loses 5%, what is the diameter at generation 10? (4) identify the event that restores size (sexual reproduction → auxospore → new full-sized frustule); (5) connect frustule silica weight to sinking rate and carbon export. Each step builds from cell biology to ecology.",
        "Dissect the Trypanosoma immune evasion strategy: (1) identify the surface coat protein responsible for immune evasion (VSG — variant surface glycoprotein); (2) explain that Trypanosoma has approximately 1,000 VSG genes but expresses only one at a time; (3) trace the evasion cycle — immune system makes antibodies to current VSG → a small number of trypanosomes switch to a different VSG gene → new VSG coats cell surface → antibodies no longer bind → parasite survives → immune system must respond again; (4) explain why this makes vaccine development extremely difficult; (5) connect to the clinical observation of relapsing waves of parasitaemia in sleeping sickness patients. Map each step to a concept from the lesson.",
        "Dissect the Paramecium conjugation sequence step by step: (1) two compatible mating types pair and form cytoplasmic bridge; (2) micronucleus in each cell undergoes meiosis → four haploid products → three degenerate → one divides mitotically → two haploid micronuclei per cell; (3) one micronucleus from each cell migrates through the bridge to the partner; (4) each cell now has one resident + one migrant micronucleus → these fuse (fertilisation) → new diploid micronucleus; (5) partners separate — each regenerates macronucleus from new micronucleus; (6) old macronucleus is destroyed. For each step, write whether genetic material is being divided, transferred, or combined, and connect step 4 explicitly to the concept of fertilisation.",
        "Perform a comparative microscopy exercise: obtain prepared slides of Euglena, Amoeba, and Paramecium. For each, measure the longest cell dimension using the field of view diameter as a scale reference. Record: cell shape, estimated size, visible organelles, and movement type if observable. Construct a three-row data table from your observations. Then connect each feature you observed to its function and supergroup — 'Euglena pellicle → flexibility without rigid wall → Excavata' — producing a complete structure-function-classification chain for each cell."
    ]
