                "Draw a fully labelled monohybrid Punnett square for Aa × Aa. Colour-code the cells: one colour for AA, one for Aa, one for aa. Draw two separate bar charts below: one for the 1:2:1 genotypic ratio, one for the 3:1 phenotypic ratio (merging AA and Aa into one bar). Annotate which cells correspond to which phenotype. Repeat for a dihybrid cross (AaBb × AaBb) on a 4×4 grid, listing all four gamete types across the top and side before filling any cells.",
                "Draw side-by-side diagrams comparing incomplete dominance and codominance using flower colour: for incomplete dominance, show red × white → pink (with a gradient arrow showing intermediate colour); for codominance, show type M × type N → MN (with both discrete antigens labelled on the cell surface). Label which is a blend (incomplete dominance) and which is full simultaneous expression (codominance). Never draw these as the same diagram.",
                "Draw a pedigree analysis decision flowchart across a full page: start with 'Is the trait sex-biased (males >> females)?' → yes → X-linked; no → autosomal. Then branch: 'Does the trait skip generations?' → yes → recessive; no → dominant. Then add X-linked recessive vs X-linked dominant tests: 'Do affected fathers have all affected daughters?' → yes → X-linked dominant; 'Do affected males have affected sons?' → yes → rules out X-linked. Draw this from memory and test against five sample pedigrees.",
                "Draw the epistasis derivation diagram for recessive epistasis: start with the 9:3:3:1 grid (four phenotypic classes labelled A_B_, A_bb, aaB_, aabb). Circle in red all classes containing aa — these are the epistatic classes. Draw arrows showing they collapse into one phenotypic class. Write the resulting 9:3:4 ratio below. Repeat for dominant epistasis (circle all classes with at least one A allele → 12:3:1) and duplicate recessive epistasis (circle classes where either gene is homozygous recessive → 9:7).",
                "Draw a three-generation pedigree for X-linked recessive inheritance: grandfather affected (X^h Y) → daughter carrier (X^H X^h) → grandson affected (X^h Y). Use the standard symbols and half-fill the carrier female circle. Annotate each individual's genotype. Then draw the alternative pedigree for autosomal recessive and identify the one pedigree feature that distinguishes the two (affected grandfather cannot pass X-linked trait to son, but can pass autosomal recessive)."
